This directory contains annotations for each species discussed in the manuscript, in GFF format. 
These are compatible with Integrated Genome Viewer, allowing for visualization of genomic regions and tinkering loci. 
IGV also requires an indexed fasta file for the corresponding genome. These can be downloaded from NCBI using the accessions provided in Table S6 and indexed with samtools faidx.
Information is contained in the following columns: 
1. Contig, matching the assemblies listed in Table S6. 
4. Start position of feature on contig. 
5. End position of feature on contig. 
7. Strand of feature. 
9. "Description" column. This contains the following substrings, which are taken by IGV and thus displayed for ease of viewing: 
- ID: (Start-stop)/Length, where these refer to the reference feature, e.g. the start and stop positions relative to the melanogaster protein or DFAM query sequence; 
accession of the reference feature (e.g. RefSeq accession of the melanogaster protein, or DFAM ID of the transposon)
genomestart_genomeend: start and end positions of feature on genome. (Required to make the feature ID unique and thus displayed by IGV.) 
- Name: same as ID. 
- Description: the E-value of the hit upon which the annotation is based, relative to the reference feature.
- Color: the IGV display color in HEX code format. This corresponds to one of three feature categories, allowing for easy visual recognition of tinkering features: 
Warm colors: gene duplicates and fragments. 
Cool colors: conserved exons. 
Shades of gray: transposons. 

Each species has only one annotation combining all of these features. If you wish to analyze one separately, you can use the three "extraction_keys" files to extract rows in the relevant annotation category: 
grep -f (extraction key file for category) (GFF) > GFF_category


